Thurston:

To start, 2/1 usually has a greater and more accurate way to raise major suit openings.

In SA or sayc, 1M-2M can be 3 or 4 trumps, 6-10 HCP 
and that's too wide a range of support for accurate follow up.

In 2/1, we usually add Bergen raises and use |cp|9|at|1M-2M|cp|2|at| as very specific: |cp|9|at|8-10 HCP with exactly 3 trumps.|cp|2|pg||at|
The Bergen variety I prefer now is Reverse: 
3@c = a 4-card limit raise, 10-12 and 
3@d = 7+-10 with 4 trumps (a 4-card constructive raise)

You'll note an overlap at the "10 end":     That is to distinguish good 10's from poor.
A's and K's = good cards,     Q's and J's = poor
1@s - 3@c with: @sAxxx @hKxxx @dKx @cxxx     (10 HCP) but 
1@s - 3@d with: @sKxxx @hQxxx @dQJx @cQx   (though also 10 HCP)|pg||at| 
After the raise, Opener will have a much better idea of when he should head towards game and when he should stop in a part score.

The next change focuses on how to try for game after a raise. 
Opener will usually need a medium hand (- 15-17 +) to try for game after 1M-2M
and the adds in distributional points after the raise, 
for example AJxxxx is worth about 2 more points for the 6th trump after supported.|pg||at|

In sayc or std, the usual way to try for game was to rebid the Major:  1M-2M-3M, 
to ask Partner if she was min. or max.|
pg||nt||
tu||
fp|2|cp|2|cs|3|ht|f|at|
But that ignores the element of FIT which is just about always more important - not "How many points partner?" 
but |cp|9|at|"Where are your points?"|cp|2|at|

If you look at the examples in the Gazette article, Opener had @sAKxxx  @hxxx  @dAKJx  @cx
and after 1@s-2@s wanted to try for game.|pg||at|

With example 3, Responder had @sQxx @hKQJx @dxx @cxxx   and game was easy, 
but with example 4: @sQxx @hxxx @dxx @cKQJx,  (the same point count) and game would go down.

3 was a "good fit" and 4 was not.
In any case, what Opener needs to know is "DO THE HANDS FIT WELL?"|pg||at|

What we use to find out is a "Help Suit Game Try": Opener bids the suit she has losers in to ask for help 
and Responder goes to game with help and stays out with no help.


Remember after 1@s-2@s we have a trump fit and that's what we're going to play in so bidding a new suit 
is NOT looking for a different trump suit - don't be greedy - one fit is enough.|pg||at|

  So with ex 3: @sAKxxx  @hxxx  @dAKJx  @cx , Opener rebids 3@h - "Can you help with my heart losers?"|pg||at| 
Responder 3:  4@s = Yes I can help
Responder 4:  3@s = no help in hearts|pg||at|

For this HSGT to work, we have to have agreed on a major: 1M-2M
and have room to say "no help" by going back to 3 of the Major.|
pg||nt||
tu||
fp|2|cp|2|cs|3|ht|f|at|
Kibby 1: What if the help suit is higher than the trump suit?|pg||at|
Thurston: If the Help Suit is higher ranking  (it will only be so after 1@h-2@h-2@s )  
then 4@h with help and 3@h without help.|pg||at|

Kibby 2: What constitutes help?|pg||at|
Thurston:  Excellent question: What is help?|pg||at| 

Usually the asker has about 3 losers
and Responder needs to be able to reduce that to no more than 2
KQJ = very good help, Ax = good help too, x = excellent as well,   Jxx or Qxx = not good enough
Kx is about 50% likely to be good help as is Kxx.|pg||at|

So with "maybe help" like Kx, I accept if the rest of the hand looks good and don't with real trash.
Qxx Kx Axxx xxxx = good,      Qxx Kx Qxxx Jxxx = not so good|pg||at|

A good thing to remember is that on the HCP scale, A's and K's are undervalued while Q's and J's are overvalued
and honors together are always better than honors all over the place: KQxx is better than Kxx Qxx|pg||at|


The key is to picture weakness with the asker and see if you can do something about it.


There will likely be more questions once we see some deals - maybe we can start those now?|
