Welcome to Paul Thurston's second session held in the BIL on February 23, 2012

^*BThurston:^*N|fp|2|at| The main focus of today's deals will be the |cs|1|at|{1NT FORCING}|cp|2|at| response to 1M,
- a frequent and critical component of 2/1.|pg||at|

- 1NT is only forcing over 1M
 (it is non-forcing over 1 minor or if Responder is a passed hand)|pg||at|

- The 1NT is usually assigned a range of approx 5-11 HCP but some will use it when a bit stronger.|pg||at|

- One main use: When holding a 3-card support for partner's Major but |cp|9|at|not enough strength to raise directly.|cp|2|at|
 (as we use 1M-2M as a "constructive raise" usually with exactly 3-card trump support)|pg||at|
 So Responder with:  @sQxx @hAx @dxxxx @cxxxx   responds 1NT to 1@s, 
 intending to show spades at his next turn - and there'll be a next turn because 1NT is forcing!|pg||at|

- Also: Responder with a good 11-12 points and 3-card support will be |cp|9|at|too strong for an immediate 2M,|cp|2|at| 
 though not enough trump support for a Reversed Bergen limit raise (3@c) and therefore responds 1NT.|pg||at|
 => With @sAJx @hQx @dKJxx @cxxxx 
 Responder bids 1NT and then shows spades at his second turn.|pg||at| 

- With the weak hand, responder will bid a minimum number at his second turn, 
 but will JUMP with the stronger example to show what is referred to as a "3-card limit raise".|pg||at|

- 1M - 2M:  a constructive raise is limited to 3-card support and 8-10 HCP: 
=>  1@s-2@s with:   @sQxx @hAQJx @dxx @cxxxx|pg||nt||
bt||
fp|2|cp|2|cs|3|ht|d|at| 
The forcing 1NT is also used with a weak hand and a long suit (usually 6+ card) of the bidder's own, 
that he's hoping to bid at his second turn.|pg||at|
The 1NT response limits the bidder's strength and the second call shows the hand type
So with:  @sx @hQxxxxx @dKJx @cxxx,    responds 1NT to 1@s 
and if Opener rebids 2@c or 2@d,   rebid 2@h to show length but not a strong hand.|pg||at|

Keep in mind that auctions that start with 1M and a 2/1 response in a new suit force the partnership to game.
Hands that in std might bid a new suit at the 2 level with 10-11 HCP can't do so in 2/1!!|pg||at|
With:  @sxx @hQxx @dAJxx @cKJxx,   Std might respond 2@c over 1@s to show 10+ hcp, 
|cp|9|at|but 1NT in 2/1|cp|2|at|    and depending on what happens next, 
Responder can then show his 11|pg||at| 

Kibby: If 1@h - 2@h is 8-10 pts and a 3-card support, 
how would Responder bid after 1@h with 6-7 pts and 3-card?  Just 1NT?|pg||at|
Thurston: Yes, precisely 1NT with 6-7 and 3-card support.
The occasional problem is that Opener will sometimes have to find a rebid when he'd be just as happy passing 1NT|pg||at|
  @sAQxxx @hKx @dxxx @cAxx   and you've opened 1@s, Partner answered 1NT
To rebid spades would promise 6 or more and you need 18-19 to raise to 2NT 
=> Opener has to "invent" a rebid in a 3-card minor.|pg||at|

Kibby: Does the sequence 1@s-1NT-2@d-2@s  promise 3 or can it just be a preference for @s 
say with a hand like @sxx @hAxx @dxxx @cKxxxx ?|pg||at|
Thurston: Yes, that preference sequence can be either a 3-card support in a weak hand or simply a preference on a doubleton.
In either case, Opener knows responder doesn't have a lot   - high cards or support - 
and will need a lot to carry on.        Let's move to the hands!                   

