^*BContinuations After Drury:^*N|at|
 
- Opener can sign-off: Show a minimum or even sub-minimum opener by returning to 2 of the agreed suit.

- Opener can try for game via HSGT: The bid of a new suit to ask for help, 2NT to ask for good trumps. 
  BUT over 2@c, to ask for @d help, you must bid 3@d.

- Opener can go directly to game based on fit, especially over 2@c where the 9th trump is present.

- Opener can make a game-forcing slam try in 1 of 2 ways:
  1. A jump to 3 of M demands a ^*Bcue-bid^*N|at|.
  2. Other single jumps in new suits are ^*Bself-splinters^*N|at| showing shortness and inviting a return cuebid 
     with the appropriate hand.
 
Over Drury 2@c, Opener can have a good hand that still isn't sure about game or even where to ask for help. 
In that case, he bids 2@d (ALERT!) an artificial rebid that says: 
"I have a real opener, tell me where you're strong, etc". 
Responder can then show a concentration of values in a new suit, a delayed splinter-bid or a bad Drury raise with scattered values by returning to 2 of the agreed suit.|pg||at|

