Thurston: 
 
Some changes occur in the 2/1 approach when Partner opens 1 Major in third OR 4th seat
To start with, responder wont have enough to force to game 
so that leaves bids like 2@c or 2@d open for other uses.

There's also some concern with a 3rd seat Opener, that Opener might not have full values to open.
For ex: After Pass - Pass - ??  I would open 1@s with: @sAQJxx @hxx @dxx @cKxxx  partly as blocking bid 
but also because I have very good spades and "almost" an opening.
The fly in the ointment sits across the table
Partner can only expect a real opening and must bid accordingly 
but you need some protection against getting too high.|pg||at|

This is where Drury comes in, as historically a 2@c response was used to show Major support 
and ask  "Do you have a real opening ?"
In 2/1 we've refined this to include 2@c as Drury with 4-card support 
and 2@d as Drury with 3-card support.
Why the difference? 
Because with a 9-card fit Opener can afford to be more aggressive in bidding game or slam 
or competing if the opponents get involved.|pg||at|

Part of why this works involves 1NT by a passed hand = no longer forcing. 
Because 1NT by a passed hand will never have 3+ cards in opener's Major.
This is what's called semi-forcing, as opener will only rebid with an unbalanced hand 
or with enough HCP to see a possible game opposite a maximum of 11 HCP with no Major fit.
So 2M by a passed hand shows 6-9 with 3-4 trump, 
2@c = 10-11 with 4 cards, 
2@d = 10-11 with 3 cards and 
3M is still preemptive with about 4-7 and 4+ trumps

